{
 "main_argument_text": "The moral principle of self‑determination obliges us to recognize a person's right to decide whether to live, provided they are competent, fully informed, and free from coercion. This right is not absolute but is the most fundamental expression of autonomy. Societal duty to preserve life does not override it; instead, it requires that we create safeguards that protect vulnerable individuals without denying competent adults their choice. Empirical evidence shows that jurisdictions permitting assisted suicide with strict criteria reduce suffering and do not increase overall suicide rates, while blanket prohibitions push people toward unsafe methods and ignore the autonomy of those who are competent.",
 "structured_analysis": {
 "claims": [
 {
 "id": 1,
 "text": "Individuals possess a moral right to self‑determination that includes the choice to end their own life when competent, informed, and uncoerced.",
 "confidence": 0.88
 },
 {
 "id": 2,
 "text": "Societal duty to preserve life can be fulfilled by safeguards that protect vulnerable people without denying competent adults the right to self‑termination.",
 "confidence": 0.82
 }
 ],
